The millipede family 
Paradoxosomatidae
is among the most diverse and widespread globally, indigenous species being absent not only from 
Antarctica
, which is self-evident, but conspicuously also from North America (

, 

; 

). The family currently comprises 1000+ species from 200+ genera, 22 tribes and three subfamilies (

; 

; 

), being especially diverse in and even dominating the diplopod faunas of Indo-Australia (

), but only marginally populating Central and North America north of 
Panama
. In contrast, the indigenous paradoxosomatid fauna of South America south of 
Panama
is quite rich, highly peculiar and diverse (140+ species).

Two major diversification centers of Paradoxosomatidae are distinguishable in South America, one in the area of southern Brazil , northern and central Chile , Paraguay and northern Argentina , the other in Peru , northern Bolivia and possibly Ecuador . The vast regions of northern Brazil , Guiana , Venezuela and Colombia have been postulated to support surprisingly few species (
,
;
). Considering six new species described below from Colombia alone, the present paper seriously questions this observation. The more so as the fauna of Venezuela contains another nine species of Paradoxosomatidae , all described by
and all of which had fallen in complete oblivion until revived recently by
.

